    public void foo(Deque&lt;String&gt; stack) {
        stack.push(bar());
        // ...;
        String xyz = stack.pop();
    }


using Deque, you have the necessary stack operations without imposing unwanted demands on the concrete type. This interface is part of the Java Collections Framework and doesn&#39;t require synchronization overhead as with the legacy Stack class.

[`SequencedCollection`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/SequencedCollection.html) probably steers closest to what you&#39;re looking for; it has the obvious downside of not existing prior to JDK21, at which point `Deque` is probably the closest you want, but, as you found, it adds a little too much.

Crucially for you, `ArrayList` __does__ implement `SequencedCollection`.

Failing all these things, there really is no option. You&#39;re presumably looking for some type that both `ArrayDeque` as well as `ArrayList` implement, as 2 somewhat arbitrarily chosen types that can trivially support fast &#39;add at end&#39; and &#39;remove last&#39; operations which is all you really need. The only one that is halfway relevant is `Collection`, but it does not offer &#39;remove from end&#39;, thus, cannot be used here.

Hence, if requiring JDK21 isn&#39;t an option, then you&#39;re either stuck making multiple methods (one that takes any `Deque`, one that takes an `ArrayList` for example), making wrappers (make your own interface, then write methods that wrap types well known to support it into an object that implements this interface):

```
public interface Stackish&lt;E&gt; {
  void push(E elem);
  E pop() throws NoSuchElementException;

  public static &lt;E&gt; Stackish&lt;E&gt; of(ArrayList&lt;E&gt; list) {
    return new Stackish&lt;E&gt;() {
      @Override public void push(E elem) {
        list.add(elem);
      }

      @Override public E pop() throws NoSuchElementException {
        try {
          return list.remove(list.size() - 1);
        } catch (IndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
          throw new NoSuchElementException();
        }
    };
  }
}
```

This would have the rather obvious annoying factor that users of your library need to wrap their collections.

As explained in [Answer by rzwitserloot][1], the [`SequencedCollection`][2] interface implemented by `List` and [`ArrayList`][3] in Java 21+ makes creating your own `Stack` class a bit easier. 

Here is some rough initial code as a proof-of-concept. Caveat: I am not an expert on [Java Generics][4]. 

First the interface.

```java
public interface Stack &lt; T &gt;
{
    public void push ( T element );

    public T pop ( );

    public T peek ( );
}
```

And an implementation. Not thread-safe. Not thoroughly tested.

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;

// Initial implementation of a stack.
// Not thread-safe.
// Uses `SequencedCollection` methods in Java 21+.
public class StackArray &lt; T &gt; implements Stack &lt; T &gt;
{
    private final ArrayList &lt; T &gt; list = new ArrayList &lt;&gt; ( );

    @Override
    public void push ( final T element )
    {
        this.list.add ( element );
    }

    public T peek ( )
    {
        if ( this.list.isEmpty ( ) ) return null;
        return this.list.getLast ( );
    }

    @Override
    public T pop ( )
    {
        if ( this.list.isEmpty ( ) ) return null;
        return this.list.removeLast ( );
    }

    // `Object` overrides.

    @Override
    public String toString ( )
    {
        return &quot;StackArray{&quot; + list + &#39;}&#39;;
    }
}
```

Usage:

        Stack &lt; String &gt; stack = new StackArray &lt;&gt; ( );
        String nothing = stack.peek ( );
        System.out.println ( &quot;nothing = &quot; + nothing );

        stack.push ( &quot;Alice&quot; );
        stack.push ( &quot;Bob&quot; );
        String bob = stack.peek ( );
        System.out.println ( &quot;bob = &quot; + bob );

        stack.push ( &quot;Carol&quot; );
        System.out.println ( &quot;stack = &quot; + stack );

        String carol = stack.pop ( );
        System.out.println ( &quot;carol = &quot; + carol );
        System.out.println ( &quot;stack = &quot; + stack );

        String bob2 = stack.pop ( );
        System.out.println ( &quot;bob2 = &quot; + bob2 );

        System.out.println ( &quot;stack = &quot; + stack );

When run:

```none
nothing = null
bob = Bob
stack = StackArray{[Alice, Bob, Carol]}
carol = Carol
stack = StackArray{[Alice, Bob]}
bob2 = Bob
stack = StackArray{[Alice]}
```


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/77572929/642706
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/SequencedCollection.html
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/ArrayList.html
  [4]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generics_in_Java

